<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Weight or Mass?</h1>=20


<p><b>Q</b>: Aren't "weight" and "mass" the same?</p>=20
<p><b>A</b>: Not really.</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/weight-n=
ormal.svg" alt=3D"weight normally shows 100" height=3D"138" width=3D"122"><=
/td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>=20
<p>An object <b>has mass</b> (say 100 kg).</p>=20
<p>This makes it heavy enough to show a <b>weight</b> of "100 kg".</p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>But the scales are only showing a guess of the mass above them!</p>=20


<h2>Gravity causes Weight</h2>=20

<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/=
gravity-guy.svg" alt=3D"gravity" height=3D"144" width=3D"306"></p>=20
<p>An object's <strong>weight</strong> is how hard gravity is pulling on it=
.</p>=20
<p>We think the weight is the same everywhere ... because we all live on th=
e surface of the planet Earth!</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/=
weight-freefall.svg" alt=3D"freefall weight is zero" height=3D"255" width=
=3D"292"></p>=20
<div style=3D"text-align: right;">=20
<p><b>But</b> in orbit it would not push on the scales at all.</p>=20
<p>The scales would show <b>0</b> ...<br>
... but the mass is still <b>100 kg</b> !</p>=20
</div><br>

<p>An object's <b>mass doesn't change</b> (unless you remove some!), but it=
s <b>weight can change</b>.</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/=
weight-moon.svg" alt=3D"freefall weight is zero" height=3D"255" width=3D"29=
2"></p>=20
<div style=3D"text-align: right;">=20
<p>On the Moon the scales would <i>wrongly</i> show <b>16,6</b><br>
for a mass of <b>100 kg</b></p>=20
<p>Because the pull of gravity on the Moon<br>
is much less than on Earth</p>=20
</div><br>

<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>


<h2>So Why Do People Say Weight instead of Mass?</h2>=20

<p><b>People often use "weight" to mean "mass"</b>, and vice versa, because=
 <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/physics/gravity.html">Gravity</a> is=
 almost the same everywhere on Earth and we don't notice a difference.</p>=
=20
<p class=3D"center"><i>But remember .. they do not mean the same thing,<br>
and they <b>can</b> have different measurements.</i></p>=20


<h2>Weight is a Force</h2>=20

<p>So ... if weight and mass are different, why are they both in kilograms?=
</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">Well, weight should not really be in kilograms!</=
p>=20
<p>I have used "kilogram" so far because that is what you see on a pair of =
scales, but it is <b>technically wrong to talk about weight in kilograms</b=
> ...</p>=20
<p class=3D"indent50px">... weight is a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.c=
om/physics/force.html">force</a> ...</p>=20
<p class=3D"indent50px">... which is measured in <b>Newtons</b></p>=20


<h2>Newtons</h2>=20

<p>The correct <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/unit.html">uni=
t</a> for force is the <b>Newton</b> (=3D1 kg=C2=B7m/s<sup>2</sup>) which i=
s abbreviated <b>N</b>.</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/down.svg" alt=3D=
"down" height=3D"49" width=3D"50"></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">On the Earth's surface gravity makes a<=
br>
<b>1 kilogram mass</b> exert about <b>9,8 Newtons of force</b></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p class=3D"larger">So a 100 kg mass really weighs about 980 Newtons on Ear=
th.</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/images/=
weight-guy.svg" alt=3D"scales in newtons" height=3D"242" width=3D"105"></p>=
=20

<h3>Why Do Scales Show Kilograms?</h3>=20

<p>Scales show Kilograms because that is what people understand best ...</p=
>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: right;">... but it is really just an <b>estimate of=
 the mass</b> above them.</p>=20
<p>Scales should really show Newtons, but that might confuse people!</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p><i>Question: how many Newtons should the scales show when <b>you</b> sta=
nd on them (hint: multiply your kg by 9,8)?</i></p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li>So the scales show an <b>estimate of your mass</b> based on the force =
your body exerts on it</li>=20
	<li>And to discover how much force your body is exerting on the scales, mu=
ltiply by 9,8 (to convert kg into Newtons)</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>


<h2>Apparent Weight</h2>=20

<p>But scales can be fooled ... because they measure a "downwards force" an=
d don't know if it is gravity or some other force!</p>=20
<p class=3D"center80"><i>Just jump up and down (gently!) on your scales at =
home to see your apparent weight change, while your mass stays the same.</i=
></p>=20
<p>So your <b>mass</b> is the same, and your <b>weight</b> is the same (bec=
ause the force of gravity hasn't changed), but your <b>"apparent" weight ch=
anges</b>. Read more at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/measure/appar=
ent-weight.html">Apparent Weight</a></p>=20


<h2>Conclusion</h2>=20

<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>Mass</b> is a measure of how much <b>matter</b> something contains<=
/li>=20
	<li><b>Weight</b> is a measure of how strongly gravity pulls</li>=20
	<li><b>Apparent Weight</b> is a measure of downwards force</li>=20
	<li><b>Force</b> is measured in <b>Newtons</b>, not kilograms</li>=20
	<li>When scales show "kg" it is just an <b>estimate</b> of the mass above =
them</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

